\chapter[Fourier Transforms and Generalized Signals]{The Fourier Transformation and Generalized Signals}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\minitoc

In this chapter, the Fourier transforms will be discussed with respect to the
Fourier series coefficients for the periodic functions. Basic properties of
the Fourier transform wil be presented. The Unit Impulse function and its
properties will also be examined.

\section{Fourier Transform and its Properties}	%1

So far, we have only dealt with periodic functions of time, eg. $f(t)$, and
their frequency domain representation using the Fourier series. It is
important to notice that the frequency spectrum of a periodic function is
discrete ($C_k$).

However, many functions that exit in the real applications are non-periodic.
The Fourier integral is introduced to find the frequency domain representation
for non-periodic functions. The evolution from the Fourier series to the
Fourier integral can be found in Chapter~3 of Baher's book, or other
references.

\begin{Def}
Given a function $f(t)$, provided that $f(t)$ has only a finite number of
maxima and minima as well as a finite number of discontinuities over
$(-\infty,\infty)$, in addition $f(t)$ is bounded, or 
\begin{equation}
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}|f(t)| dt \qquad\mbox{is finite} 
\end{equation}
the fourier transform (FT) of $f(t)$ is given by

\begin{equation}
F(\omega)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(t)e^{-j\omega t}dt
\end{equation}
and the inverse Fourier transform of $F(\omega)$ is defined by 
\begin{equation}
f(t)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}F(\omega)e^{j\omega t}d\omega
\end{equation}
\end{Def}

$f(t)$ and $F(\omega)$ constitute a Fourier transform pain and may be
expressed by
\begin{equation}
f(t) \fpair F(\omega) 
\end{equation}

By convention, the following notations are used:
\begin{align}
F(\omega) &=\F[f(t)] \\
f(t) &=\F^{-1}[F(\omega)] \\
\intertext{In general, the Fourier Transform $F(\omega)$ of a function $f(t)$ is a complex function of $\omega$.}
F(\omega) &=|F(\omega)|e^{j\phi(\omega)} \\
 &=R(\omega)+jx(\omega) 
\end{align}

where $\omega$ is a continuous variable and $|F(\omega)|$ plotted against
$\omega$ is the continuous amplitude spectrum of $f(t)$ and $\phi(\omega)$
plotted against $\omega$ presents the continuous phase spectrum.

{\raggedright Note:\\}
\begin{tabular}{r@{:}c@{$\rightarrow$}l}
function & periodic & nonperiodic \\
spectrum & discrete & continuous \\
Fourier & series & integral (transform) \\
\end{tabular}

\begin{Exa}
Given a function
\begin{equation}
f(t)=\begin{cases}
	e^{-bt} & t\geqslant 0 \\
	0 & t<0 \\
	\end{cases}
\end{equation}

where $b>0$, find its Fourier Transform.

\begin{align}
\intertext{Solution:}
F(\omega) &=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(t)e^{-j\omega t} dt \\
&= \int_{-\infty}^{0}0 e^{-j\omega t}dt+\int_0^{\infty}e^{-bt}e^{-j\omega t}
dt \\
&= \int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-(b_j\omega) t} dt \\
&= -\left.\frac{1}{b+j\omega} e^{-(b+j\omega)t}\right|_0^{\infty} \\
&= \frac{1}{b+j\omega}
\end{align}

