\subsection{Fourier Transform of Causal Signals}
For a real causal function
\begin{equation}
f(-t)=0 \qquad t>0 
\end{equation}
it can be expressed as
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cc@{+}c}
f(t)=&\frac{1}{2}[f(t)+f(-t)]           & \frac{1}{2}[f(t)-f(-t)] \\
     & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\Updownarrow}  & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\Updownarrow} \\
     & \frac{1}{2}f(t)                   & \frac{1}{2}f(t) \\
\end{array}
\end{equation}
or
\begin{align}
	f(t) &= 2 \times \mbox{even part of $f(t)$}\\
	     &= 2 \times \mbox{odd part of $f(t)$}
\end{align}
Using linearity of the F.T.
\begin{align}
f(t) &\fpair 2R(\omega) \zdtag \\
f(t) &\fpair 2jx(\omega) 
\label{eq3-lin}
\end{align}

provided that $f(t)$ is casual and real. Equation~\ref{eq3-lin} states that a
real causal function is uniquely determined by either the real or imaginary
part of the Fourier Transform.

The relation between $R(\omega)$ and $x(\omega)$ of the $F(\omega)$ of a
real causal function $f(t)$ is stated by the Hilbert Transform\index{Hilbert
Transform}.

