\subsection{Shifting in Frequency}

If 
\begin{align}
f(t)&\fpair F(\omega) \\
f(t)e^{\pm j \omega_0 t} &\fpair F(\omega \mp \omega_0) \\
\F\left[f(t)e^{\pm j \omega_0 t}\right] &\\
&= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} f(t) e^{\pm j\omega_0 t}e^{-j\omega t} dt \\
&= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} f(t) e^{-j(\omega \mp \omega_0) t} dt \\
&= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} f(t) e^{(-j\omega ')t} dt \\
&= F(\omega ') \\
&= F(\omega \mp \omega_0)
\end{align}

\subsection{Modulation}

Using the linearity and the shifting in frequency properties of the Fourier
Transform.
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{2}f(t)\left[e^{j\omega_0 t)}+e^{-j\omega_0 t}\right] &\fpair
\frac{1}{2}\left[F(\omega-\omega_0)+F(\omega+\omega_0)\right] \\
 \Updownarrow \qquad &\\
f(t)\cos \omega_0 t  &\fpair
\frac{1}{2}\left[F(\omega-\omega_0)+F(\omega+\omega_0)\right]
\end{align}

In this case $\cos \omega_0 t$ is called the carrier\index{carrier} and $f(t)$
is called modularity\index{modularity signal}\index{signal!modualarity} or
baseband signal\index{baseband signal}\index{signal!baseband}. The function
$\cos \omega_0 t$ is said to be modulated in amplitude by the signal $f(t)$,

The spectrum of the modulated signal is obtained from that of $f(t)$ by
shifting the baseband spectrum by $-\omega_0$ and $\omega_0$ producing two
side-bands\index{side bands} as shown in Figure~\ref{f3-modulation}.

