Therefore, the Fourier transform spectrum $F_p(\omega)$ of a periodic
function $f_p(t)$ with period $T$, is the infinite train of equidistant
impulses, ($\omega_0$ apart). Each impulse is of strength $F(k\omega_0)$ which
is the value at $k\omega_0$ of the Fourier Transform of the non-periodic function $f(t)$
defining $f_p(t)$ over one period.

\begin{align}
\intertext{If we define}
C_k(k\omega_0) &= \frac{1}{T}F(k\omega_0) \zdtag \\
&= \frac{1}{T}\int_{T/2}^{T/2} f(t)e^{-j k \omega_0 t} dt \\
\intertext{the Fourier Transform of the periodic function $f_p(t)$ is:}
F_p(\omega) &= 2\pi \sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty} C_k \delta(\omega-k\omega_0) \label{eq3-ftper} \\
\intertext{The inverse Fourier Transform of the $F_p(\omega)$ is given by }
f_p(t) &=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty} C_ke^{j k \omega_0 t} \label{eq3-invftper}
\end{align}

( Comparing Equation~\ref{eq3-ftper} and~\ref{eq3-invftper} with the Fourier
series coefficients
\begin{align}
f(t) &=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty} C_ke^{j k \omega_0 t} \\
C_k &= \frac{1}{T}\int_{-T/2}^{T/2} f(t)E^{-j k \omega_0 t} dt \mbox{)}
\end{align}


Fourier series is a special case of the Fourier transform.

\begin{Rem}
Any periodicity in the time domain results in impulses in the Fourier Spectrum
\end{Rem}

